      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "GCI for primary QoI (NIH) must be less than 5% at the mesh density used for production runs. Asymptotic convergence must be demonstrated.",
      "rationale": "Three-mesh GCI study yields GCI_fine = 0.9% for NIH, well below the 5% threshold. Asymptotic convergence ratio 0.97 confirms solution is in the asymptotic range. Production runs use the 22 M-cell mesh. Discretization error is the smallest contributor to total uncertainty budget. Exceeds Gradation 2 requirement; Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions (fluid properties, temperature, flow rates, rotational speed) must be documented with measurement uncertainty and must correspond to the simulated boundary conditions within stated tolerances.",
      "rationale": "FDA benchmark in-vitro tests conducted with porcine blood analog (glycerol-water, viscosity 3.5 ± 0.1 mPa·s at 37°C). Temperature maintained at 37 ± 0.5°C. Flow rates measured with Coriolis flowmeter (±0.5% FS). Rotational speed verified with optical tachometer (±5 RPM). All boundary conditions in CFD model set to experimental mean values; uncertainty propagated through UQ framework. Gradation 2 met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (NRMSE or equivalent) between CFD predictions and experimental measurements must be computed for primary QoI and must meet the acceptance threshold defined in the validation plan.",
      "rationale": "NIH comparison: mean relative error 6.2% across five operating points; all within ±15% acceptance band. Shear stress NRMSE 8.3% across 12 PIV planes, within 10% threshold. H-Q curve agreement within 5% at all design points. Systematic bias assessed via Bland-Altman analysis: mean bias −0.003 g/100 L (negligible). Gradation 2 met for all three QoIs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The QoIs used in validation (NIH, shear stress, H-Q curve) must be directly relevant to the clinical decision metric (relative hemolysis index RH) and must be measurable with sufficient fidelity in the validation experiment.",
      "rationale": "NIH is the direct precursor to the regulatory RH metric (RH = NIH_device / NIH_predicate). Shear stress fields drive the power-law hemolysis damage model. H-Q curve confirms hydrodynamic operating point fidelity. All three QoIs are measurable in the FDA benchmark setup with documented instrumentation. Clinical relevance chain is complete and documented in the validation plan. Gradation 2 met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments must use a geometry, fluid, and operating regime sufficiently similar to the COU device and conditions. Any extrapolation beyond the validated space must be justified.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, which is the same device class (centrifugal, rotary) as the COU device. Blood analog properties bracket clinical blood viscosity range. Operating points (2.5–7.5 L/min, 2500–3500 RPM) span the COU operating envelope. Geometric scaling factor between validation and COU device is 1.03 (within 5% — no significant extrapolation). Gradation 2 met."
    },
    {
